---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Blog — Perqed" activeNav="blog">

  <section class="blog-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Blog</p>
      <h1 class="header-title">Build log</h1>
      <p class="header-desc">
        Milestones, deep-dives, and lessons from building an autonomous proof engine.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="blog-list">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>April 07, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">mcts</span>
          <span class="tag">rag</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/adversarial-trees-and-polite-infrastructure/">Adversarial Trees and Polite Infrastructure</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          Why we abandoned raw LLM generation in favor of Lakatosian feedback loops, local LanceDB vectors, and native UNIX sockets.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/adversarial-trees-and-polite-infrastructure/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>April 4, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">infrastructure</span>
          <span class="tag">cryptography</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/migrating-to-trytet-v3/">Migrating to Trytet v3.0 & Cryptographic Fuel Bounds</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          How we replaced our execution backend with Trytet v3.0, integrated Ed25519 deterministic fuel validation natively via TypeScript, and resolved IPv6/Linux-Bwrap overhead anomalies systematically.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/migrating-to-trytet-v3/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>April 3, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">neuro-symbolic</span>
          <span class="tag">falsification</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/perqed-v3-falsification-engine/">Perqed v3.0: Autonomous Falsification and Interdisciplinary Synthesis</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          An overview of our update shifting Perqed from a formal verification wrapper into an autonomous hypothesis engine backed by native empirical validation.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/perqed-v3-falsification-engine/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>April 2, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">combinatorics</span>
          <span class="tag">optimization</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/vdw-orchestrator-bounds/">Orchestrating Combinatorial Searches for Van der Waerden Bounds</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          We implemented dynamic CLI-driven orchestration to decompose and execute search strategies for Van der Waerden partition boundaries natively.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/vdw-orchestrator-bounds/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>April 2, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">neuro-symbolic</span>
          <span class="tag">lean4</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/zero-copy-tactical-reasoning/">Zero-Copy Tactical Reasoning: A Case Study</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          How our engine successfully routed an ArXiv paper into 7 empirical Python domains, passed the failure trace through an adversarial Red Team auditor, and translated <code>push_neg</code> directives natively down to zero-latency Lean 4 compilation bounds using bwrap.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/zero-copy-tactical-reasoning/">Read post →</a>
      </article>
      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>April 2, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">devops</span>
          <span class="tag">lean4</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/hardening-agency-topology/">The 55GB Leak: Zero-Copy Sandboxes and Agency Topologies</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          How we addressed a critical Mathlib storage leak by routing around the sandbox and <code>--ro-bind</code>ing the global cache, while unifying our model infrastructure into a localized <code>agency.json</code> Registry.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/hardening-agency-topology/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 31, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">xstate</span>
          <span class="tag">reactive</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/xstate-orchestration/">Reactive Math: Migrating Perqed's Core to XState v5</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          We transitioned our neuro-symbolic engine to a reactive, 10-state DAG architecture to improve orchestration efficiency.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/xstate-orchestration/">Read post →</a>
      </article>
      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 31, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">hackernews</span>
          <span class="tag">academia</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/jar-rejection/">Rejected for Poor Repo Hygiene</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          How an organizational oversight involving historical Goldbach scripts affected our Journal of Automated Reasoning Torus Decomposition submission.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/jar-rejection/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 30, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">rag</span>
          <span class="tag">lean4</span>
          <span class="tag">neuro-symbolic</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/mathematician-in-a-box/">Building a Mathematician in a Box: RAG, Red Teams, and Falsification</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          How we integrated the ArxivLibrarian into the Architect to ground model outputs, established a Red Team for adversarial review, and optimized Lean 4 computational paths.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/mathematician-in-a-box/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 21, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">number-theory</span>
          <span class="tag">lean4</span>
          <span class="tag">spectral</span>
          <span class="tag">fft</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/goldbach-stress-test/">Exploratory Benchmarking: The Goldbach Conjecture</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          The Goldbach conjecture was utilized as an exploratory benchmark for our autonomous proof engine, encountering structural obstructions and mapping them to established mathematical foundations.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/goldbach-stress-test/">Read post →</a>
      </article>
      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 19, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">rag</span>
          <span class="tag">llm</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/librarian-and-skill-injection/">Autonomous Mathematical Literature Analysis</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          From graph coloring to universal domains: how we enabled Perqed to analyze academic papers,
          integrate mathematical skills, and optimize file system interactions.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/librarian-and-skill-injection/">Read post →</a>
      </article>
      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 18, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">engineering</span>
          <span class="tag">llm</span>
          <span class="tag">ramsey</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/teaching-the-architect-to-panic/">Managing Search Stagnation in the Architect</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          Implementing fail-safe mechanisms for stalled search processes, including multi-stage basin escape and prioritized mathematical triage.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/teaching-the-architect-to-panic/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 16, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">engineering</span>
          <span class="tag">z3</span>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/how-we-got-our-stack/">We Got Stuck, and Then We Had an Architecture</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          SA hit E=12 and wouldn't move. Instead of tuning hyperparameters, we asked the
          right question: does a solution even exist? Z3 answered in seconds — UNSAT — and
          we almost threw the result away. This is the story of how a stuck search run
          became a solver stack.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/how-we-got-our-stack/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 15, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">engineering</span>
          <span class="tag">simulated-annealing</span>
          <span class="tag">lean4</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/torus-decomposition/">Finding Needles in a 6<sup>215</sup> Haystack</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          The paper proves the m=4 and m=6 torus decompositions are correct.
          This post covers what the paper skips: the energy function bug, the
          12× incremental speedup, and the TypeScript-to-Lean handoff.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/torus-decomposition/">Read post →</a>
      </article>

      <article class="post-card">
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 14, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">milestone</span>
          <span class="tag">lean4</span>
          <span class="tag">deepseek-r1</span>
          <span class="tag">prover-v2</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="post-title">
          <a href="/blog/first-autonomous-proof/">Two Autonomous Proofs, Two Paradigms</a>
        </h2>
        <p class="post-excerpt">
          Two models prove n + m = m + n in Lean 4 — R1:8B as a strategist (77s, 1 shot) and
          Prover-V2 as a speedrunner (33s, 7 iterations). Plus: the quantization trap.
        </p>
        <a class="read-link" href="/blog/first-autonomous-proof/">Read post →</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .blog-header {
    padding: 80px 0 40px;
  }

  .header-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  .header-desc {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    max-width: 460px;
  }

  .blog-list {
    padding-bottom: 80px;
  }

  .post-card {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    padding: 36px 0;
  }

  .post-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 12px;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .post-meta time {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .tag {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    background: var(--accent-purple-subtle);
    color: var(--accent-purple);
    padding: 3px 10px;
    border-radius: 100px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .post-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }

  .post-title a {
    color: var(--text-primary);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .post-title a:hover {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .post-excerpt {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    max-width: 560px;
  }

  .read-link {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .read-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .blog-header { padding: 48px 0 24px; }
    .header-title { font-size: 1.9rem; }
  }
</style>
